In [54]:
# Evaluate each model
results = {}
In [55]:
for name, model in models.items():
    if name in ['Support Vector Regression', 'Neural Network']:
        model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    else:
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    
    results[name] = {'MSE': mse, 'MAE': mae, 'R': r2}

Key Positive Contributors to Life Expectancy :

The 'HIV' variable has the highest importance, indicating that deaths due to HIV/AIDS have a significant negative impact on life expectancy. This highlights the critical need for effective HIV prevention, treatment, and education programs to reduce mortality rates associated with the disease. Adult Mortality:

The mortality rate for adults aged 15-60 is also a significant factor. Efforts to reduce adult mortality through better healthcare services, disease prevention, and health promotion activities can improve overall life expectancy. Infant Deaths:

The number of infant deaths per 1000 population is a crucial factor. Reducing infant mortality by improving maternal and child healthcare services can significantly enhance life expectancy. Income Index:

A higher income index (HDI in terms of national income per capita) is positively associated with life expectancy. Economic prosperity allows for better healthcare infrastructure, access to medical services, and improved living conditions, which contribute to longer life spans. Malnourished5_9 and Malnourished10_19:

Malnourishment in children aged 5-9 and 10-19 negatively affects life expectancy. Addressing malnutrition through better food security, nutrition programs, and public health interventions is essential for improving long-term health outcomes. Schooling:

Education, as measured by the number of years of schooling, is positively associated with life expectancy. Education is linked to better health awareness, higher income levels, and improved access to healthcare services. Other Considerations GDP:

The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita has a moderate importance, suggesting that while economic factors are crucial, they are not the sole determinants of life expectancy. Under-five Deaths:

Similar to infant deaths, the number of deaths under 5 years of age is an important factor, emphasizing the need for robust maternal and child healthcare services. Vaccination Rates (Measles, Polio, Diphtheria, Hepatitis):

Immunization rates for diseases like Measles, Polio, Diphtheria, and Hepatitis have some importance but are not among the top factors in this model. This may indicate that while vaccination is crucial, other healthcare services and socioeconomic factors play a more dominant role in determining life expectancy.
